Here is the full **testsmells.org 19-smell catalog** audit for `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`.

---

## Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| High | 3 | 3 |
| Medium | 1 | 1 |
| Low | 0 | 0 |
| **Total** | **4** | **4** |

*Integration-test calibration applied — this class is tagged `[TestCategory("Integration")]`, so Mystery Guest and Eager Test norms are relaxed.*

---

## Findings by Severity

### ❶ Sleepy Test — **High**

**Test:** `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` (line 87)

```csharp
Thread.Sleep(3000);  // ← blocks runner for 3 full seconds
```

Even in integration tests, `Thread.Sleep` is a smell. It's non-deterministic — if the system is slow the test fails; if it's fast the test wastes time. Per Camara et al. (SAST 2021), sleepy tests are a strong predictor of flakiness.

**Fix:** Poll with a timeout or use a `TaskCompletionSource` / event handle:

```csharp
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
while (!_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id))
{
    await Task.Delay(50, cts.Token);
}
Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id));
```

---

### ❷ Conditional Test Logic — **High**

**Test:** `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` (lines 101-108)

```csharp
if (loaded is PremiumUser premium)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(premium.DiscountRate > 0);
}
else
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded!.Name);
}
```

One branch or the other is **never executed** — you're silently hiding a testing gap. If `loaded` is always a regular `User`, the `PremiumUser` path is dead code with zero coverage.

**Fix:** Write two separate tests, each with a deterministic setup:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_RegularUser_ReturnsName()
{
    _repository.Insert(new User("eve@example.com", "Eve"));
    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com");
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded!.Name);
}

[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_PremiumUser_HasDiscount()
{
    _repository.Insert(new PremiumUser("eve@example.com", "Eve", 0.1m));
    var loaded = (PremiumUser)_repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com")!;
    Assert.IsTrue(loaded.DiscountRate > 0);
}
```

---

### ❸ Assertion-Free Test (Unknown Test) — **High**

**Test:** `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` (lines 113-119)

```csharp
public void BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }
    // ← No assertion. Passes as long as no exception is thrown.
}
```

This gives false confidence — the method name *claims* it runs without errors, but if `Insert` silently drops records, this test still passes.

**Fix:** Assert on the outcome:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void BulkInsert_PersistsAllRecords()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }

    var all = _repository.ListAll();
    Assert.AreEqual(100, all.Count);
}
```

---

### ❹ Assertion Roulette — **Medium**

**Test:** `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` (lines 35-38)

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name);
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email);
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0);
```

Four assertions with **no message parameters**. When one fails, MSTest reports the assertion type and expected/actual values but no human-readable context. Per Peruma et al. (ESEC/FSE 2020), this is one of the most prevalent smells.

**Fix:** Add a message to each assertion:

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded, "User should be retrievable after insert");
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name, "Name should match inserted value");
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email, "Email should match inserted value");
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0, "Persisted user should have a positive Id");
```

---

## Smells Scanned — No Findings (15/19 clean)

| Smell | Result |
|-------|--------|
| Mystery Guest | ✅ Clean — uses in-memory SQLite; also integration-calibrated |
| Eager Test | ✅ Clean — multiple repo calls are appropriate for integration scope |
| Magic Number Test | ✅ Clean — `3` in `ListUsers` is contextually obvious (3 inserts); `10` in concurrency test likewise |
| Sensitive Equality | ✅ Clean — no `ToString()` comparisons |
| Exception Handling | ✅ Clean — no try/catch in tests |
| General Fixture | ✅ Clean — `_connection` and `_repository` used by every test |
| Ignored/Disabled Test | ✅ Clean — no `[Ignore]` or skipped tests |
| Duplicate Assert | ✅ Clean — no repeated assertions |
| Lazy Test | ✅ Clean — each test targets distinct behavior |
| Constructor Initialization | ✅ Clean — uses `[TestInitialize]` properly |
| Default Test | ✅ Clean — class is meaningfully named |
| Redundant Print | ✅ Clean — no console output |
| Redundant Assertion | ✅ Clean — no tautological asserts |
| Resource Optimism | ✅ Clean — no assumed-present external files |
| Empty Test | ✅ Clean — no empty method bodies |

---

## Prioritized Remediation Plan

| Priority | Smell | Test | Effort | Why First |
|----------|-------|------|--------|-----------|
| 1 | Assertion-Free Test | `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` | ~2 min | False pass risk — this test verifies nothing |
| 2 | Conditional Test Logic | `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` | ~5 min | Hidden coverage gap — one branch is dead |
| 3 | Sleepy Test | `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` | ~10 min | Flakiness risk + slows suite by 3 s per run |
| 4 | Assertion Roulette | `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` | ~2 min | Diagnostic clarity — low risk but easy to fix |

**Bottom line:** 4 out of 8 tests carry smells, but the remaining 4 are cleanly written. The high-severity items (#1-#3) represent real testing gaps or flakiness risk and should be addressed first. The codebase setup/teardown pattern and naming conventions are solid.
